        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "9ccf91c6-c29a-4dac-bb87-c92b7e444b57",
        "text": "Three Chinese scientists came to Cambridge for graduate study in 1937: [[Lu Gwei-djen]], [[Wang Ying-lai]] and Shen Shih-Chang (沈詩章, the only one under Needham's tutelage). Lu, daughter of a [[Nanjing]] pharmacist, taught Needham Chinese, igniting his interest in China's ancient technological and scientific past. He then pursued, and mastered, the study of [[Classical Chinese]] privately with [[Gustav Haloun]]."
      },
      "after": "0c22df31-6c1d-47e5-954e-7f600fbb4c75",
      "id": "9ccf91c6-c29a-4dac-bb87-c92b7e444b57",
